A standard deontic encoding is O(Act(a, α) → Prior(Consent(a, α))).
Equivalently, to make the required step explicit, write O(SeekConsent(a, α) before Act(a, α)).
This says it is obligatory that whenever agent a performs action α, valid consent for α has already been obtained.
If you want the prohibition form, use F(Act(a, α) ∧ ¬Prior(Consent(a, α))), where Fφ ≡ O¬φ.
The strongest practical formulation is O(¬Act(a, α) U Consent(a, α)), meaning the agent must refrain from acting until consent holds.
Choose α to range over only consent-sensitive actions if the obligation is not meant to cover everything the agent does.
